+-------------------------------+--------------------------------------+
| +--------------------------+  | **Overnight Reflection Question**    |
| | **Multi-stage attack     |  |                                      |
| | chains**                 |  | BeEF can execute JavaScript in a     |
| |                          |  | browser that visits a hooked page.   |
| | A Browser Hooking attack |  |                                      |
| | (BeEF) can hook a        |  | Command Injection can run arbitrary  |
| | victim\'s browser and    |  | OS commands on the server.           |
| | make it execute          |  |                                      |
| | commands. Command        |  | **If you could chain these two       |
| | Injection can execute    |  | capabilities together --- starting   |
| | arbitrary OS commands.   |  | from a phishing email sent to a BBC  |
| | Module 7 shows you how   |  | employee --- what would each step of |
| | these two techniques     |  | the complete attack look like?**     |
| | connect into a single    |  |                                      |
| | end-to-end attack chain. |  | *There is no single right answer.    |
| +--------------------------+  | Think about what the attacker        |
| | **SSRF in depth**        |  | controls at each stage, and what     |
| |                          |  | they need to move to the next one.*  |
| | Server-Side Request      |  |                                      |
| | Forgery moves the        |  |                                      |
| | attacker\'s access from  |  |                                      |
| | the public internet to   |  |                                      |
| | the server\'s internal   |  |                                      |
| | network. Cloud           |  |                                      |
| | environments are         |  |                                      |
| | particularly vulnerable  |  |                                      |
| | --- the AWS metadata     |  |                                      |
| | endpoint                 |  |                                      |
| | (169.254.169.254) holds  |  |                                      |
| | IAM credentials that     |  |                                      |
| | grant full account       |  |                                      |
| | access.                  |  |                                      |
| +--------------------------+  |                                      |
| | **Injection as a design  |  |                                      |
| | failure**                |  |                                      |
| |                          |  |                                      |
| | Module 7 closes the      |  |                                      |
| | loop: every injection    |  |                                      |
| | vulnerability you\'ve    |  |                                      |
| | seen this afternoon      |  |                                      |
| | results from the same    |  |                                      |
| | design failure --- no    |  |                                      |
| | boundary between data    |  |                                      |
| | and code. Module 7 shows |  |                                      |
| | the systematic defences  |  |                                      |
| | at each layer: input     |  |                                      |
| | validation, output       |  |                                      |
| | encoding, and runtime    |  |                                      |
| | controls.                |  |                                      |
| +--------------------------+  |                                      |
